docs.text: i swear i have seen the edge before .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: in fact , it reminded me of the bear , the river wild , and other various films mixed into an entirely different film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: however , the edge has done something that most action films should do , and that is add heart and characters we like to the plot .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: in doing so , the edge draws many more suspenseful moments out of cliched scenes than , say , the peacemaker .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: unfortunately , because of those overused moments , we can pretty much guess the outcome of the film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but leave it to screenwriter david mamet to add humor and a few surprises to mess with your head .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: one surprise , in particular , left me smiling just because mamet actually had the guts to add it to his script .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: action films are a dime a dozen in hollywood , and while they are somewhat successful at entertaining us , they lack the one thing which would make them a more respected genre : intelligence .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: even horror films have learned this , a genre which is probably the least respected of them all .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the river wild was one of the best action/suspense films i have seen from the 90s .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the intelligence of the screenplay , and the suspense drawn from the realistic characters is nearly unmatched to this day .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the edge has the intelligence and smart characters , but this time the lack of originality is the downfall .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i must admit that it was very suspenseful , and had an original third half , but the first hour and a half is riddled with cliches and plot holes .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this is an example of the final act saving the film , instead of the other way around ( as in the lost world ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: if only the screenplay had maintained the final thirty minutes' intensity , it could have become a great action film ( and i use the term loosely ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the edge is pretty much a survival-of-the-fittest film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but taking scream's lead , the edge makes fun of the genre's cliches , and then uses them ( though not quite as effectively ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: charles morse ( anthony hopkins ) is the main character , a rich and very intelligent man who wonders what the accumulation of all this knowledge has brought to him .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: for once , we don't immediately care for the main character .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: instead , we like bob ( alec baldwin ) , a photographer who is going to take pictures of charles' wife , mickey ( elle macpherson ) , out in the wilderness .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: they board a plane and head to a cabin somewhere in the arctic .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: charles' birthday is the same day , and he receives a gold watch from his wife , and a pocket knife from bob .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: as action films go , these items do have importance to the rest of the story , but quite a bit more than we first expect .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: soon , however , bob wants to find a native to shoot pictures of because of his " personality . "
docs.label: positive

docs.text: charles , bob , bob's assistant steve ( harold perrineau ) , and the pilot head off to find him , and as shown in the previews , hit a flock of birds flying south for the winter .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: down the plane goes , the pilot is killed , and the three are left to survive in the wilderness .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: director lee tamahori is aware of the silly plot which is about to follow , and therefore has to create original ways to approach the situations .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: he succeeds often enough for us to enjoy the film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: take , for instance , the entire man-hunting bear plot .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this has been done many times in films with different animals , and even bears .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but given the charles' intelligence , and bob's uncertainty , many of the cliches are given fresh twists .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: even charles himself seems to have seen these action films before .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: my favorite line of the film comes from charles : " most people die in the wilderness because they didn't do the one thing that could save their life . . .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: thinking . "
docs.label: positive

docs.text: despite the predictability of the main plot , a subplot develops late in the film which took me by surprise , and made me smile when i realized that everything isn't as it seems anymore .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i have to write cautiously as to not reveal this surprise , so instead i will avoid it entirely .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the first two-thirds of the edge have many humorous moments to push it along , and some of charles' survival techniques seem possible , even making fire from ice .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: tamahori is able to create a lot of suspense from the stalking bear , but whenever the bear is present , the characters lose all sensibility .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i have always wondered why characters in films walk over a log to get across water .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: why not do what an intelligent person would and crawl across ?
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i guess getting chased by a bear makes your thought process turn off for a while .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: thankfully , we already have begun to care for the characters , and so we let this small detail slide .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but some of the technical details are awkward , such as the nice stitching done on the fur coat that charles and bob make ( where did they get thread and needles ? ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the acting of the film is highly above average for a film of this nature , and borders on phenomenal .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: anthony hopkins gives a terrific performance , creating his most likeable and layered character since remains of the day .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: hopkins usually brings greatness to his roles , but here he exceeds at gaining the audiences' sympathy , something he definitely did not do in silence of the lambs .

docs.text: alec baldwin gives one of his best performances i have ever seen ( it sure is better from his fair game ) .

docs.text: baldwin can be a good or a bad character , and here he succeeds at both in a way .

docs.text: you can never quite guess if he is a nice or a vllainous character until the end , and baldwin is able to handle the double-natured photographer .

docs.text: elle macpherson gives a good performance , albeit slight .

docs.text: she isn't in the film all that much , but for the scenes she does have , she handles as an actress , not as a model .

docs.text: harold perrineau is a good actor , and his scenes are nice and underplayed .

docs.text: this film is a nice change from the mindless action most of us are used to , but too many cliches bog it down .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: director tamahori has created a very smooth and suspenseful action film out of recycled parts .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: david mamet's script , though , has a lot of humor to keep the first hour afloat , and the acting is solid .

docs.text: the best thing about the script is the ending which doesn't end with the normal high-strung action sequence , but with a small detail involving a certain gift .
